Short correct answer

In bin/rails, require_relative "../config/boot" starts the Rails boot process by setting up Bundler and load paths, but it does not fully boot or initialize the application.

What bin/rails actually does (simplified)

Typical bin/rails:

#!/usr/bin/env ruby
APP_PATH = File.expand_path("../config/application", __dir__)
require_relative "../config/boot"
require "rails/commands"

Line-by-line meaning
1ï¸âƒ£ require_relative "../config/boot" âœ…

ğŸ“ Bootstrapping step

What it does:

Loads config/boot.rb

Sets up Bundler

Loads gems from Gemfile

Inside config/boot.rb:

ENV["BUNDLE_GEMFILE"] ||= File.expand_path("../Gemfile", __dir__)
require "bundler/setup"


ğŸ‘‰ This prepares the Ruby environment
ğŸ‘‰ Rails is NOT initialized yet

2ï¸âƒ£ APP_PATH = ...config/application

Points Rails to your app definition

Not executed yet â€” just a reference

3ï¸âƒ£ require "rails/commands"

ğŸ“ Command dispatch

Loads Rails CLI

Executes rails s, rails c, etc.

For rails s, it eventually:

loads config/application.rb

loads config/environment.rb

calls Rails.application.initialize!

Timeline clarity (important)
bin/rails
  â†“
require config/boot.rb   âœ… (Bundler only)
  â†“
rails/commands
  â†“
load config/application.rb
  â†“
load config/environment.rb
  â†“
Rails.application.initialize!  âœ… (real boot)

Key distinction (very interview-important)
Step    Purpose
config/boot.rb  Prepare Ruby + gems
application.rb  Define app + configs
environment.rb  Initialize app
One-line interview answer â­

require_relative "../config/boot" in bin/rails starts the bootstrapping process by setting up Bundler and the gem environment, but the actual application boot and initialization happen later via config/application.rb and Rails.application.initialize!.

Common mistake (avoid this)

âŒ â€œconfig/boot.rb boots the Rails appâ€
âœ… â€œconfig/boot.rb bootstraps the Ruby environmentâ€